  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws are established through various international conventions, agreements, and organizations that work to create a global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. Key international frameworks include:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**  \n     Also known as the Vienna Convention, it was the first international treaty to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**  \n     Known as the Palermo Convention, it requires signatory states to criminalize money laundering and establish AML measures.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**  \n     The Merida Convention obligates countries to implement measures to prevent and combat money laundering associated with corruption.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Its **40 Recommendations** are the global blueprint for AML and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) efforts.  \n   - The FATF also identifies high-risk jurisdictions (through its \"grey list\" and \"black list\") and encourages member countries to enforce AML/CFT measures.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has issued several AML Directives (e.g., the **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**) to harmonize AML laws across member states. These directives require EU countries to implement strict AML measures, including criminalizing money laundering and enhancing transparency.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee's **Core Principles for Effective Banking Supervision** includes guidelines for banks to implement AML measures, such as customer due diligence and suspicious transaction reporting.\n\n### 5. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**\n   - These organizations provide technical assistance and support to countries in implementing AML/CFT measures and assessing compliance with international standards.\n\n### 6. **Interpol and Egmont Group**\n   - Interpol assists in international cooperation to combat money laundering, while the Egmont Group facilitates information sharing among financial intelligence units (FIUs) worldwide.\n\n### Key AML Measures and Requirements\n   - **Criminalization of Money Laundering:** Countries are required to make money laundering a criminal offense.  \n   - **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Financial institutions must identify and verify their clients.  \n   - **Suspicious Activity Reporting:** Institutions must report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities.  \n   - **Record-Keeping:** Maintaining records of transactions for a specified period.  \n   - **International Cooperation:** Sharing information and coordinating efforts across borders.\n\nWhile these international frameworks provide guidelines, it is up to individual countries to implement and enforce AML laws through their domestic legal systems. Non-compliance can result in sanctions, restrictions, or reputational damage.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
